<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: PLAN TO BOOST PATROLS NEAR SCHOOLS APPROVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seeking to ensure the safety of schoolchildren, the City Council on Wednesday 
approved a plan to boost police patrols on streets surrounding schools in 
gang-plagued neighborhoods in Watts. 
</P>
<P>
City Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky said the stepped-up patrols, which will cost 
$150,000 through the end of the school year, would help "create an environment 
in which young people who want to get an education can do so without taking 
their lives in their hands." 
</P>
<P>
Deputy Police Chief William Rathburn said the department's Southeast Division 
now has six officers patroling "pedestrian corridors." But he said that "has 
not been enough" to ensure the safety of students. 
</P>
<P>
With the new money, the department will be able to deploy 10 officers in five 
cars each school day, Rathburn said. They will patrol streets around Jordan and 
Locke high schools and nearby junior highs and elementary schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
